'''Periscopic''' is a [[Portland, Oregon]] based data visualization firm founded by [[Kim Rees]] and Dino Citraro in 2004.<ref name="cv">{{cite web |last1=Cowles |first1=Dan |title=Periscopic |url=http://web.archive.org/web/20151112073341/http://www.adobe.com/inspire/2013/12/interview-periscopic.html |archivedate = 2015-11-12 |website=Creative Voices |publisher=Adobe.com |accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref> Its motto is "Do good with data."<ref name="Riley 2012">{{cite web | last=Riley | first=Theresa | title=How America's Workforce has Changed Since 1960 | website=BillMoyers.com | date=2012-06-18 | url=https://billmoyers.com/2012/06/18/how-americas-workforce-has-changed-since-1960/ | access-date=2018-10-05}}</ref> They have worked with such clients as [[Google]], [[General Electric|GE]], and the [[Bill & Melinda Gates Foundation]]. Rees is also an advisor to the [[U.S. Congressional Budget Office]].<ref name="Wilson 2013">{{cite web | last=Wilson | first=Mark | title=What’s The Secret To Great Infographics? | website=Fast Company | date=2013-03-25 | url=https://www.fastcompany.com/1672207/whats-the-secret-to-great-infographics | access-date=2018-10-05}}</ref> The company won an APDU Data Viz Award in 2017 for their work on the US Patent and Trademark Office's website PatentsView, a project they worked on with the [[US Department of Agriculture]], the [[American Institutes for Research|American Institutes for Research]]’s Center for the Science of Science and Innovation Policy, the [[University of California at Berkeley]], and Twin Arch Technologies.<ref name="Buff 2017">{{cite web | last=Buff | first=Brendan | title=Announcing: 2017 APDU Data Viz Awards Winners | website=APDU: The Association of Public Data Users | date=2017-08-15 | url=http://apdu.org/2017/08/15/announcing-2017-apdu-data-viz-awards-winners/ | access-date=2018-10-05}}</ref><ref name="li">{{cite web |title=Dino Citraro Co-founder & Design Director at Periscopic |url=https://www.linkedin.com/in/dino-citraro-a6538b7 |website=LinkedIn |accessdate=5 October 2018}}</ref>
